\section{Part 1: Meta-learners for job training
evaluation}\label{part-1-meta-learners-for-job-training-evaluation}

The dataset ``job\_training\_updated.csv'' contains information about
12,000 individuals who either participated or did not participate in a
job training program, including: - training: Binary indicator of whether
individual participated in training (treatment) - earnings:
Post-training annual earnings in thousands of dollars (outcome) - age:
Age of individual - education: Years of education - prior\_earnings:
Earnings before training program - employment\_history: Years of prior
employment - urban: Binary indicator of urban residence

\subsection{Task 2}\label{task-2}

Next, you shall estimate an orthogonal learner, using decision trees as
the method for predicting both the treatment and the outcome. Please
follow the following steps:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Train a decision tree model using rpart() to predict training from
    all confounders using the full dataset. For classification trees,
    use method=``class'' and for the control parameters use: cp=0,
    minbucket=5, maxdepth=30 (i.e.,
    control=rpart::rpart.control(cp=0,minbucket=5, maxdepth=30)).
  \end{enumerate}
\item
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
  \setcounter{enumi}{1}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Train a decision tree model using rpart() to predict earnings from
    all confounders using the full dataset. For regression trees, use
    method=``anova'' and the same control parameters: cp=0, minbucket=5,
    maxdepth=30 (i.e., control=rpart::rpart.control(cp=0,minbucket=5,
    maxdepth=30)).
  \end{enumerate}
\item
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
  \setcounter{enumi}{2}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Make predictions of treatment (using model from a, with
    type=``prob'') and outcome (using model from b) for all
    observations.
  \end{enumerate}
\item
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
  \setcounter{enumi}{3}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Calculate residuals for all observations: X\_tilde = X - X\_hat,
    Y\_tilde = Y - Y\_hat.
  \end{enumerate}
\item
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
  \setcounter{enumi}{4}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Estimate the ATE by regressing Y\_tilde on X\_tilde using lm().
  \end{enumerate}
\item
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
  \setcounter{enumi}{5}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Report the ATE. How does it compare to your OLS estimate in \#1?
  \end{enumerate}
\item
  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
  \setcounter{enumi}{6}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Which of the two methods do you trust more? Can you think of any
    aspect of the implementation of the orthogonal learner which could
    bias its estimate?
  \end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Task 3}\label{task-3}

Given your conclusions in \#2, do you think either of the following two
changes to the setup of the orthogonal learner could improve the ATE
estimate? (i) switching from a decision tree to a random forest, (ii)
add cross-fitting. Motivate.

Cross-fitting means to predict out-of-fold to block contamination
whereby the orthogonal learner does not bias the residuals in hold-out
towards 0. To adress the high variance of the trees by prohibiting the
most important variables to dominate the trees. The negative aspect of
forests that they are less interpretable is not relevant here since we
are only interested in predicting the effect of the confounders to X and
Y.

\subsection{Task 4}\label{task-4}

Now you shall implement the two updates discussed in \#3. Please do the
following:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\alph{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  Divide your data into 5 folds (hint: you can use createFolds() from
  the caret package).
\item
  Create a for-loop which in each iteration i does the following:

  \begin{enumerate}
  \def\labelenumii{\roman{enumii}.}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Train a random forest model using randomForest() (with ntree=200 and
    mtry=2) predicting training from confounders on data in folds ̸= i.
  \item
    Train a random forest model using randomForest() (with ntree=200 and
    mtry=2) predicting earnings from confounders on data in folds ̸= i.
  \item
    Use models from (i) and (ii) to predict treatment (with
    type=``prob'') and outcome for ob- servations in fold i.
  \item
    Calculate residuals X\_tilde and Y\_tilde for observations in fold
    i.
  \item
    Store residuals from fold i.
  \end{enumerate}
\item
  Combine dataset of residuals and regress Y\_tilde on X\_tilde using
  lm().
\item
  Report the estimated ATE. Do you trust this estimate more than those
  in \#2, and if so why (or why not)?
\end{enumerate}
